Mr Wilson said 'exceptional circumstances' meant the trial could not go ahead because Morrison had 'buried his head in the sand', and he had stopped communicating with his legal team, according to the Shields Gazette.

Mr Wilson told the court that Morrison had lost his business as a result of his commitment to his charitable work. 

He said the grandfather had stopped opening his mail and said he had 'disengaged from society.'

